nal service is required. Use an in-process Spring Boot context with local beans annotated with Resilience4j annotations and resilience4j.* test properties. If testing actuator endpoints, expose only the needed endpoints with management.endpoints.web.exposure.include or instantiate endpoint/health beans directly to avoid adding a web server unless necessary.\",\n./stats/io.kotest/kotest-assertions-core-jvm/6.1.11/execution-metrics.json:53:      \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n./stats/io.kotest/kotest-assertions-core-jvm/6.1.11/execution-metrics.json:54:      \"agent_guidance\": \"No environment variables or system properties are required. Meaningful coverage should come from Kotlin/JUnit tests that exercise the assertion APIs directly, including successful assertions and caught failure paths such as shouldBe, shouldContain, shouldThrow, inspectors, clues, or soft assertions. Do not require the Kotest runner just to use kotest-assertions-core.\",\n./stats/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot-kafka/4.1.0/execution-metrics.json:77:      \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n./stats/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot-kafka/4.1.0/execution-metrics.json:78:      \"agent_guidance\": \"\",\n./stats/org.scala-lang/tasty-core_3/3.2.2/execution-metrics.json:47:      \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n./stats/org.scala-lang/tasty-core_3/3.2.2/execution-metrics.json:48:      \"agent_guidance\": \"No environment or system properties are required. For meaningful coverage, tests can exercise TastyBuffer, TastyReader, TastyFormat, TastyHash, and TastyHeaderUnpickler directly, using constructed compatible TASTy header bytes or the .tasty resources packaged inside the target JAR. Avoid depending on TASTy files freshly emitted by the current scaffold Scala compiler unless compatibility is verified, because tasty-core 3.2.2 only accepts its compatible TASTy format version.\",\n./stats/org.apache.parquet/parquet-jackson/1.12.2/execution-metrics.json:58:      \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n./stats/org.a